caption: Excellent udon. Very safe and cozy backyard with yurts. Great service.
DELICIOUS!!! Best Udon I’ve had in a while.
Great chicken wings! Udon chip with tofu cream cheese is unique.

Everything was just perfect until they found out their card reader did not work. They told me we could just go but I felt awful not paying for their good food and kind hospitality. This review is the least I could do other than paying another visit in the near future.

Excellent Japanese restaurant which specialises in Udon. The staff were so friendly and service very quick. Currently dining in the open igloos is pretty comfortable. I ordered the chicken karage with rice (better value than the appetiser) which was really nice. It was very lightly battered and the spices scrumptious. Came with rice and a bit of cabbage. I want to come back to try to noodles too!

Hanon was great. The chicken karage was outstanding with plenty of spice; buried in a mound toasted chile peppers. Tantan udon was tasty, but the real star was the ambiance, their igloo shelters were cozy and intimate offering a welcome respite from standard outdoor dining experiences.

Probably the best udon I’ve ever had in New York City. If you guys like Raku, you would love this place even more. They definitely take longer to cook the food, but that’s because everything is made fresh and it really shows when you eat it. I had the curry udon and the tantan udon, both exceptional and full of flavours!

Affordable price!!! FOOD: Udon was excellent and broth very tasty. You know it was good because the fish cake was very bouncy and mushroom was packed with flavor. Surprisingly good was the veggie karaage which was made from fried yams SERVICE: Service was very quick and efficient. Everyone who served us was very kind. For covid they have these igloos in the back garden that are well lit with heaters. We came around 7pm on a Friday night and there was no wait  Overall, solid spot in williamsburg for udon. We liked it far more than nearby Samurai Mama

Had previously eaten at this gem, and the udon is perfection (the kitsune is a balance between sweet and salty and is presented with distinct layers). The private outdoor domes are magical and warm, even/especially on a cold rainy night.
The udon is nice and fresh.
Sooooo gooood! It’s as good as the udon I had in Kyoto. The backyard is cute too!
Hanon is one of my favorite spots in Williamsburg. The quality is always excellent and every dish is perfection.
Ordered delivery, packaging is super thoughtful and they truly care about the quality of the food. It was amazing

Delicious udon and great atmosphere! Would recommend the curry beef udon and the vegetable tempura! I have come to this restaurant many times throughout the pandemic and every time it seems they manage to create a more COVID-safe environment. When I visited in November they had complimentary group igloos with heating out back!

The udon was amazing and they have a great outdoor seating out back. The only grievance was they forgot our appetizer and had to bring it out after the udon was already served. They didn’t offer to comp it or anything after we did get it which would have been nice. I’ll still be going back regardless cause the food was so good!
This restaurant is amazing! The food is delicious, the staff very nice, and the backyard set up so pretty and cosy. I totally recommend this place, it's a real gem in Brooklyn!

Terrible experience. Waited for 1hr 15 minutes for our udons. Udons are overcooked and flavors are just decent. One waiter even lost his patience when I asked about the status of the udons and the other appetizer they had forgotten about, and we only asked once. Later he apologized to me, probably realizing his misstep. I’m giving it one more star only because I can tell they’re really understaffed and this is a difficult time for restaurants in general.  We arrived around 7:20 and put in our order around 7:30. The first appetizer, tamago, arrived promptly. Flavor was good and the presentation was lovely. We now put in another appetizer order, tempura, and they apparently didn’t put it in. We waited until 8:20 and noticed that the waiters had not come to patio with food or even come at all for a while, so we presumed they were tied up.  At 8:30 I went in and asked about the status, a waiter told me that there were still two orders before us and it usually took around an hour for udon to be ready around dinner time.  An hour to fulfill an udon order is normal - is that what you mean? And if you told us that when we ordered, do you think we would have stayed for dinner?  I’d think udon broth is mostly precooked. What step in udon preparing would take an hour to complete? I can only presume they handle takeout and dine-in order altogether, which is bad management and I don’t think they deserve the benefit of doubt.  I then asked about the other appetizer order we put in. He didn’t answer directly and it was not on the order ticket he showed me. He went in and checked with the waitress we put in the order with.  So I waited for him to come back, while waiting for the bathroom. Another waiter checked in with me. I told him I was waiting about the status of our order. He snapped and said he “already” told my friends that it was a full house tonight.  Hello? I was not at the table when you updated the status with my friends, was I?  A minute later he circled back with me and apologized, saying again it’s a full house.  At 8:40, we got our other appetizer, the tempura. Flavor was good, but nothing worth waiting an hour for. And apparently it took less than 10 minutes to prepare since they added the order. Around 8:45, we finally got our udons. Right after, all the people that came in after 8 got their orders too.  Udons were overcooked. We got Kitsune Udon, Tori & Kinok Udon, and Niku Udon. Maybe it’s different preference, but growing up in Taiwan and been to Japan a few times, I prefer udons to have some kind of al dente texture. The only thing I was delighted about my kitsune udon was the sharpness from the thin peels of yuzu.  I really wanted to like Hanon. They have such a cute backyard and you can tell the owners put a lot of thoughts into the restaurant. They dining ware was very sophisticated and they kept the tables far apart. Still, very disappointed. Not sure if I’ll ever come back. My friends said udon at Raku is way better.

One of my absolute favorite go to spots. Been here many times pre covid and ordered a couple times since. The food is just incredible. Simple menu but with many offerings. The udon is really amazing and pretty spot on to what I’ve had in Japan. Also if you dine in the service is great, super friendly and attentive staff. Don’t skip dessert!
Absolutely loved it! I had the Tan tan udon, the portion is very good and the meat is super rich in flavor. The atmosphere is great and the staff is also very friendly. Highly recommend:)
Slaps hard

Authentic Japanese udon that did not disappoint.  Many people recommended their dipping noodles, I also like their udon salad. Udon, salad and their dressing are the great match!  Their tempura is also worth trying.  Ask for today's special too.
worst service ever .it takes long time to make a food .

Was in the mood for some noodles and hanon did not disappoint. They have fresh udon served hot or cold. I had dipping udon with the two kinds of noodles. It was fantastically delicious and the noodles were perfectly executed. The karage was also nice and light and moist. The service was good. The tables were socially distanced. Masks were enforced. They have a cute garden in the back but also some seating out front. Totally worth checking out.
Authentic and delicious - made me feel like I was back in Japan
I tried several things and my favorite is Tantan udon!! SO good
Food was amazing. I recommend the curry udon
Brilliant takeout strategy for broth, udon and topping all packed in separate compartments. Felt like date night at home. Amazing.

Some of the best takeout we’ve ever had! We used to frequent this restaurant before lockdown, and loved it, but were concerned as to whether it would travel well. We need not have worried, the presentation, instructions and experience were as good as sitting at a table in situ. Keep doing what you’re doing guys, you are fantastic.
My wife and I love this izakaya restaurant. Their food and service is awesome. Their udon is perfection. We will definitely be regulars.
Unfortunately, the food was definitely not worth the wait. We waited over 30min for our food and it was very bland. We ordered two different kinds of hot udon dishes and both were mediocre at best.
Terrible service, waited forever for the food and my udon was way too salty.
Amazing udon and smaller bites, and very down to earth service. Loved the servers here!
A place to go for both authentic Japanese food as well as western fusion cuisine.

I've been here twice. First time was for lunch after a soft opening and it was great! I remember the food being on point and the service being spot on.  We came for dinner this time around and while it's wildly popular, the tofu salad was great and the curry wagyushu was amazing - silky udon and tender succulent slices of beef - the bar seating up against the wall was just dirty. There were spots all over the wall of broth that was slurped up by previous customers. It's a little bit of a mood killer....
Great food and great service.

This place is great for the udon.  There other dishes are tasty too, but not at the same level.    My go-to is the Niku Udon and Washu-Gyu Curry Udon.  Service is always good here.  I’ve been several times and staff usually recognizes me which is nice.
So tasty. Really fabulous food
It was well made but didn't amaze me. I had the curry udon and wanted it to have more of a curry consistency. The mentai udon that my friend got though was really good!!!

The house made udon is adding wheat germ and bran to the white flour, which made the texture is bit rough but also chewy and healthy.  The tempura shrimp and shiitake mushroom are perfectly battered and fried, golden and crispy outside and not overcooked inside in the meanwhile. We also enjoyed the red bean jelly, which satisfied our sweet tooth but not too heavy to finish the meal.

as vegetarians on a cold winter day our hot entree options were limited to two, and we ordered both. they were perhaps too authentic for us: the whipped mountain yam bowl was extremely salty, yolky, and fishy, and the tofu/seaweed bowl was full of soggy tempura flakes, which must be a thing in Japan. All the toppings were fried and what we tried seemed not to really go with the soup. we did like the appetizers (also fried) so three stars.

I came here on a weekend evening around 6PM, and it was quite full when we got there. Our waiter asked if we've ever been, and upon our denial, he gave us recommendations. I had seen on Yelp the cold udon, so I wanted that. We both ended up getting the cold dipping noodle with duck, and our orders came out quite quickly. The noodles are delicious, perfectly chewy and awesome. The soup was mediocre as it just tasted like diluted soy sauce, and the duck was quite terrible. There was some weird coating outside the duck that made it taste really bad, and there wasn't much flavor to it. I could tell the duck was probably sitting out for a while, and it was really bad. I would not recommend the duck at all. If not for the duck, I would've given this spot 5 stars, but the duck was bad enough to ruin my meal that I do not want to come back (and it's also what made my meal so expensive). A normal dipping sauce is $10 pre-tax pre-tip, the duck dipping soup was $18 pre-tax pre-tip. Paying $8 (and then some for tax and tip) for 4 pieces of really bad duck was not good. The amount of food was good, but I just really did not enjoy the duck. Service was also quite pleasant, as the waiters were friendly, approachable, and prompt in refilling our waters and clearing our plates.
Everything I have tried so far has been great. I want to go back and order all the tempura. Service felt like I was back in Japan
Best noodles I’ve had so far in ny. Will DEF be back to try all the other noodles.
tan tan udon was amazing !! definitely coming back
low key spot with friendly staff and great food. cozy interior. noodles are amazing and apps are good too.

Friendly and accommodating service; we arrived late but they made room for us so we didn't have to wait long. The curry udon was rich and flavorful, but if you're interested in something milder there are plenty of options!
Really good udon!
Friendly staff, but a little pricey.

This is a pretty popular Udon spot that gets crowded quickly due to it’s smaller size, so you should come between 6-7pm to make sure you’re seated quickly. The food is pretty good - the hot udon dishes especially. I would stay away from any root-based dishes - they have some unappetizing preparations of those.

Noodles are good but customer service is poor. We came here to celebrate a birthday and had heard great things about the food. I had brought a cake all the way from Chelsea to celebrate the birthday. They charge a $7pp cake cutting fee, which is fine. But when they cut my cake, they threw away 1/4 of it. They didn't even mention it until we asked where a layer of our cake was. In my opinion, if you mess up this bad, you should offer something as a courtesy. Maybe don't charge us $50 for cutting a cake and then throwing away 25% of it. They offered us more dessert which we clearly didn't need.  Go for the dipping udon, skip the rice dishes.  Again, food was good but the customer service left a bad taste in my mouth. Won't return.

11.9.19 - Generally good food. The fried chicken is tender and seasoned well. The TanTan Udon and Jouya Udon were okay. The TanTan lacked enough pork, but the broth was good. The Jouya was ordinary, even as a dish for simplicity. The udon, not my preferred taste and texture.  The Octopus and Avocado salad was good with decent amount of octopus and good size chunks of avocado; the dressing was just right.  The service could not have been better and the space is simple and comfortable. They have patio, but I think it's only for warmer weather.  Overall, I will not repeat. We went to Raku Soho the week before, which we liked a lot more in terms of quality, quantity, and price if food, but their staff can use a lot of cleaning up. Merge the Hanon staff with Raku menu and I think you have a very good restaurant.  Hanon takes reservations, but plan a day or two in advance.
Wonderful and simple udon. The noodles are bouncy, the broth is soothing, the restaurant vibe is relaxed.

This is a quality place that is getting more and more popular every day. Definitely get an udon dish but their other options are excellent as well (Octopus salad). The udon with beef-curry broth was awesome, I recommend extra noodles every time.  I don’t believe they except reservations ahead so expect a little bit of a wait. If you need to, Montesacro and Barcade right next door are perfect to kill time. Only thing that would make this place better is a liquor license. TBD I hope
Great service and great atmosphere but every time I go there I get sick :( I like their appetizers than udon dish here.
Kitsune udon is amazing! Best udon around!
The yam dipping sauce is dope
Poor taste, very poor. Service unnoticeable. Not going back.
Lovely udon noodle restaurant in Williamsburg. Very good location; excellent food and lovely staff~

Fresh udon made on-site with flour imported from Japan. Very special blend, one with bamboo that makes the udon green but that's only available cold. It was a cold day so we only ordered hot noodles. The veggie/seafood kakiage and the beef curry using were delicious.  Great texture and flavor. Must try if you are in the area.  Went back the second time for summer cold udon and just as impressed as first time.  Visit if you can. You can taste the craftsmanship. If you order the mountain yam dipping sauce, be sure to mix it well before dipping. It's very foamy.
Tempura was really authentic but Udon I felt was a bit overpowered by spinach and yuzu.  Noodles them selves were perfectly cooked and chewy.  Wish they had liquor license.  Overall good experience.

Consistently great food- have tried 10 or so dishes so far, impressed every time. Also worth noting- great service the dozen or so times I’ve been; the manager is consistently particularly cool to chat with about food, Japan, et al, and the staff make good menu Recc’s on the regular. Try the tempura egg. Curry Udon is great too.
I had great spicy cod cold noodles. The yam sauce lacked a little punch. They are still waiting for liquor license but the oolong tea was good supplement. Good service and fast turn around.
Amazing soba from this newly-opened restaurant. Highly recommended to get the mix soba, just to taste the difference in flavor. Presentation and service are top notch as well.
Reasonably priced, big portions of traditional udon are served by friendly, attentive and impeccably dressed staff.
Delicious!

A very generous four stars of my part because although the udon is good, the entire meal remained mostly forgettable. Hanon will be more appealing however once they have a liquor license and start seating people in the outside patio.
Great food, friendly staff and relaxing atmosphere. Highly recommended.
Great food!  We love this restaurant. They are so friendly, it is intimate and the noodles/stock is so delicious.  So glad to have such a gem in our neighborhood.
Authentic Japanese style udon with friendly staff.
Excellent
Kinda bland honestly, maybe the dipping style is better.
Cold udon with duck breast broth 👍
Really enjoyed everything we tried here. The broth for the agedashi tofu is really good.

Overall a pleasant experience. I ordered the tempura dipping set (tempura seiro) with both selections of available udon. Server recommended the sesame dipping sauce.  I really enjoyed the chewy bite of the udon. Honestly, I can't tell the difference in taste (newb palette) but it's interesting to say the least.  The place is certainly worth another visit. I will get the soup next time.  The reason for the 4 stars is because of the tendon. The whole point tempura is the crispy tempura batter. The tendon tempura was unfortunately dipped or spent too much time in sauce, making the batter soggy. Would be significantly better if the sauce was put on top of the bed of rice first then have the tempura drizzled with sauce instead. Maybe this is a regional thing?

Nice cozy spot, cool that they serve dipping noodles and tendon - two of my favorite dishes from Japan. Unfortunately, the tempura in the tendon was completely soggy which negates the very point of tempura! Also no less than 5 different waiters waited on us at different points throughout the meal which was weird. All in all, this place has potential but I was disappointed to give away $19 for soggy tempura on rice.

One of the newest additions to the metropolitan/Lorimer stop eats! They opened this year and today was my first time visiting. I love noodles, and this udon place definitely has caught my attention. Has great atmosphere/abivence. I had ordered one of their chilled udon sets and it was certainly a different dining experience. Most times, I perfer hot udon in broth. But today I wanted something cooler to counter the NY spring heat. Perfect choice. You get a plate of freshly made noodles (chilled) and you soak your noodles in the broth/sauce they give you and eat. Not to be mistaken as a broth, the sauce was flavorful and impactful without being too saturated with odd flavors. I do admit, I was a bit sad that the tempura wasn't alot bigger, cause I loveee tempura but! The tempura was light and fluffy as it should be and it was just enough to fill me. 5/5 will go again.

Excited to stumble upon this new udon place the other day! Got the cold udon half and half and was extremely pleased by the texture and chewiness of the noodles. Interior was clean and cozy, and the staff was very warm and friendly. Will definitely return.
Simply excellent udon. No doubt one of the best in the city. Quality of the udon itself is really good. It's got a great texture and flavour, and it's most obvious with the cold udon.
Fantastic food, cute spot - get the braised pork.

The atomosphere is so welcoming the staff is super patient and knowledgable about the their products one thing that can be difficult to understand is the menu but the staff can be of help. Their bathroom is amazing heated seats and a bidet and they have a little speaker with music and they have an outside area that wasnt opened because of the weather but it looked super cute and the appitizer i had was soooo good

I love this place because it's small and homey. Can't wait for them to open the back deck this summer. Service is great and the food is dope. The menu is a little complicated but they take their time with you and explain things well.  Also, the person that complained about the kitchen being closed 15 minutes before close is super entitled.
This is some of the best udon I've had in NYC. Service was perfect, the noodles were out of this world. No liquor license when I was there, but with udon of this caliber it doesn't really matter.
I was recommended by my friend about this place. They serve not reasonable price food, but the taste of the food are so good. It was amazing, Everything was fresh and packed with flavor.
What a delight
Excellent. This was one of the best Japanese meals I’ve had in a long time. Service is amazing. Fried chicken and pork appetizers are a must have
Loved it!
I dont know how the food is. I was excited to try as I read good things but the kitchen doesnt close at 3 as per the website. At 2:35 they were already done for the afternoon.
A beautiful place and incredible delicious food!
Stumbled upon a gem, great nooooddddllleeessss 🍜
An absolute gem and definitely worth traveling from Manhattan for. I’d say this is the best udon shop in town and I’m drooling at the recollection of these fine slippery chewy noodles as I’m writing.
Wonderful experience. Delicious and intriguing food with strong attention paid to detail and quality. Pleasant atmosphere and staff.

Not since living in Kyoto have I had udon this good. The noodles are exactly right, the broth is exactly right, but the toppings are better than that. With the toppings, Hanon innovates in subtle, refined ways that make all the difference. Some baby bok choi with the kakiage udon for a touch of grassy bitterness; or a bit of lemon zest in the kitsune udon. Lemon zest in the broth of the kitsune udon! It’s transcendental.

The appetizers were pretty amazing. The cabbage steak, and the fried egg plant were special and unlike any other appetizers I've ever had.  I had the curry udon and it was fantastic - not overpowering, tasty, filling, and really great on a cold day.  Staff couldn't be nicer, and the whole place is very... japanese! :-) Would go back for sure.
Amazing flavors and textures straight out of Japan. A lovely experience and food you can't find elsewhere in NYC.
